reason.tex:
\begin{align} \frac{x^2}{x^2+4x+3} &= a + \frac{b}{x+1} + \frac{c}{x+3} \\ \implies x^2 &= a\cdot (x^2+4x+3) + b\cdot (x+3) \\ &+ c\cdot (x+1) \\ &= ax^2 + (4a + b + c)x + (3a + 3b+c) \end{align}\\ %text
On \underline\text{comparing coefficients}, we can see that
% \begin{align} a &= 1 \text{ (coefficient of }x^2)\\ \underbrace{4a + b + c = 0}_{x} &\implies \underbrace{b + c = -4}_{a=1} \\ \underbrace{3a + 3b + c = 0}_{\text{constant term}}&\implies\underbrace{3b +c = -3}_{a=1}\\ \implies b &= \frac{1}{2}\text{ and } c = -\frac{9}{2} \end{align}
